<h1>Policies and Procedures</h1>


<p>The Electronic Theses and Dissertations program is a joint project of the
  Emory Libraries, the Emory Graduate School, and Emory College. For all questions
  relating to graduation requirements and the preparation of your thesis or dissertation,
  please refer your questions to the Graduate School (or Emory College for undergraduate
  honors theses), or your individual graduate program (or undergraduate department).
  For questions regarding the electronic submission of your thesis or dissertation,
  please contact the Emory Library through our ETD listserv email:
  <a href="mailto:etd-admin@listserv.cc.emory.edu">etd-admin@listserv.cc.emory.edu</a>. </p>

  
<h3>I. Policies and Procedures for Graduate Students</h3>

<p>Please refer to the <a href="https://gs.emory.edu/resources/progress.php?id=7">Graduate
   School website</a> to see the prerequisites for graduation,
    instructions on preparing your theses and dissertations, links to necessary
    forms, and other useful resources. </p>
    
<h4>1. Access</h4>
<p>All students submitting an ETD will be able to choose either (1) "open
  access" meaning the full-text of their work will be available in Emory's
  repository immediately after graduation; or (2) "restricted access;" meaning
  the publication of their work will be delayed for a specific period of time.
  The current restricted access choices for authors are (i) six months, (ii)
  one year, (iii) two years, or (iv) six years. The<em> access restriction period
  expires automatically</em> after the end of access restriction period; it is
  the responsibility of the author to request an extension of the access restriction
  period if necessary. Such requests should be sent to:
  <a href="mailto:etd-admin@listserv.cc.emory.edu">etd-admin@listserv.cc.emory.edu</a>.</p>

  <p>The ETD repository was created by the university to increase access to the
  work of Emory Scholars. The University hopes that authors submitting their
  work here who chose to restrict access to their work will choose the shortest
  possible restriction period, taking into consideration the constraints of their
  individual situations and the demands of their particular academic field. We
  restate the Graduate School's statement on access issues:</p>
  
  <div style="border:3px double #666666;background-color:#CCCCCC;padding:15px">
    <h3>A Note on Access</h3>

  <p>The move to electronic theses and dissertation creates unparalleled opportunities
  for wide and timely dissemination of the work of Emory graduates, creating
  greater opportunities for your scholarly work to be recognized by others in
  your field.</p>
  
  <p>It also creates new parameters for copyright and publishing, and it is important
  that you make an informed decision about the terms of access to your dissertation
  or thesis. In particular, you need to learn about two issues:</p>

  <ol>
    <li>If your dissertation contains articles that were published in scholarly
     journals or elsewhere, you need to make sure that your terms of access are
     compatible with the permissions granted by those journals or other entities.</li>
  
    <li>If you plan to publish some or all of your dissertation/thesis, you need
     find out whether the journals and publishers who would be likely to publish
     your work regard an electronically accessible dissertation as a prior publication.</li>
  </ol>
  
  <p>The policies on both these issues vary widely across fields and publishers,
  and are changing fast. Take the time to investigate the conditions in your
  field, and make your decisions with accurate and up-to-date information, and
  in consultation with your advisor.</p>
  
  <p>The Library offers regular information sessions on copyright and intellectual
  property. You can find dates and times on the ETD website. Take advantage of
  these sessions to learn about issues that will be important throughout your
  scholarly career.</p>
</div>

  
