<h4>3. Intellectual Property</h4>
<p>All theses and dissertations produced at Emory are the intellectual property
  of the authors. Authors may disseminate those works as they see fit, but they
  are also solely responsible for the contents of their thesis or dissertation.
  Please refer to our
   <a href="<?= $this->url(array('controller' => 'docs', 'action' => 'ip')) ?>">Intellectual
   Property page</a> for helpful information on author's
  rights and the use of previously copyrighted materials. All questions regarding
  patentable content in a thesis or dissertation should be referred to the
  <a href="http://www.ott.emory.edu/">Office of Technology Transfer</a> and your
  advisor.</p>

<h4>4. Patentable Material</h4>
 <p>If any of your work in your thesis or dissertation has patent implications,
  it is important that you not submit your work electronically. Please confer
  with your faculty advisors and/or <a href="http://www.ott.emory.edu/">Emory's
   Office of Technology Transfer</a>
  for guidance. Once the proper patent filings have been made, you may choose
  to proceed with your electronic submission.</p>
  <h4>5. Paper Copies</h4>
  <p>The library will no longer produce paper copies of theses and dissertations,
    and will not hold a copy on its shelves. The electronic copy will be the
    university's official copy of your work. Please contact your graduate program
    for information on their requirements on paper copies.</p>
  <p>See our information page on
  <a href="<?= $this->url(array('controller' => 'docs', 'action' => 'boundcopies')) ?>">Obtaining
  Bound Copies of Your Theses and Dissertations</a>
  for information on paper copies for your personal use.</p>
  <h4>6. Proquest</h4>
  <p>All doctoral dissertations will continue to be sent to Proquest where they
    will be made available under the terms set in their submission agreement.
    (See <a href="https://gs.emory.edu/resources/progress.php?id=7">Graduate School Website</a> for necessary paper forms.) Master's theses
    may be sent to proquest at the discretion of the author. Please be aware
    that
    most students should choose from one of the two "traditional publishing"
    options for Proquest. Proquest offers two "open access" options
    which give you an opportunity to place your work in their open access repository,
    a
    service offered without cost by Emory. (Students may choose to use the Proquest
    open access repository if they choose to do so, however, if they choose to
    pay the additional fee.)</p>
  <p>Proquest does not offer an access restriction period of greater than 2 years.
    If you choose Emory's six year option, it is your responsibility to see that
    Proquest is informed that you wish an embargo term of greater than two years.</p>
